Relatively early in your textbook (Quinn and Keough 2002), youâll be introduced to an example data set that was generated by Lovett et al. (2000). They studied the chemistry of forested watersheds in the Catskill Mountains in New York State. Weâll use these data for an introduction to using LaTeX to write symbols and equations and to become more familiar with R, RStudio, and github.

Lovett et al. (2000) chose 39 sites (observations) on first and second order streams and measured the concentrations of ten chemical variables averaged over three years, and four watershed variables (maximum elevation (m), sample elevation (m), length of stream (m), watershed area (ha)).:

  1. \(NO_3^-\) (NO3),
  2. Total Organic \(N\) (TON),
  3. Total \(N\) (TN),
  4. \(NH_4^{2+}\) (NH4),
  5. Dissolved Organic \(C\) (DOC),
  6. \(SO_4^{2-}\) (SO4),
  7. \(Cl^-\) (CL),
  8. \(Ca^{2+}\) (CA),
  9. \(Mg^{2+}\) (MG),
  10. \(H^+\) (H).

Data import

The data are provided as a comma-separated-value (.csv) âflat-file databaseâ by Quinn and Keough (2002), âlovett.csv.â Iâve imported this text file using the read_csv() function provided by the readr package (Wickham et al. 2023) included in the tidyverse metapackage (Wickham et al. 2019). This function will create a âtibbleâ which is a special case of data.frame, the standard approach for storing data in memory for most R operations. In R jargon, a data.frame is a particular class of list, and lists are flexible R objects that may contain elements of different types like â numbers, strings, vectors and even other lists. A list can also contain a matrix or a function as its elements. In R, the term vectors may be more specific or more broad than what you may have been introduced to in a math class. Typically, when you see reference to vector in the context of R, itâs referring to atomic vectors, that is, they are data structures that contain a single type of data:

  • logical â TRUE or FALSE,
  • integer - numeric data that are whole integers,
  • double - double precision floating point format (i.e.Â numbers with decimals),
  • character - non-numeric data,
  • complex â includes imaginary numbers, or
  • raw - information in byte form.

In fingernails-on-the-chalkboard grima, base-R also considers lists and atomic vectors to be specific types of more broadly defined vectors.

df1 <- read_csv("lovett.csv", show_col_types = FALSE)

After importing the data, you may wish to check to make sure the command did what you wanted, or to have a look at the variables included in the data.frame. Like most operations in R, there are a number of ways to do this, but my preferred approach is to take advantage of the RStudio IDE. If you click on the Environment tab in the upper right hand window of RStudio, you will get a list of all of the objects currently being stored in active memory for R. If you click on the small arrow icon (expand) to the left of df1 (our data.frame) you will see the details of the list of atomic vectors in the tibble. Note that STREAM is a vector of character data while all of the other vectors contain numeric data.

If you click on the spreadsheet icon to the far right of the data.frame name, RStudio will open a viewer that you can use to examine the data contained in the data.frame. This is purely a viewer and has no editing capabilities.

In the expanded listing of the contents for df1, you may notice the dollar symbol, â$â â this is actually an operator in R that allows you to address a specific part of an object. For example, in the code block below I ask R to print the elements of the vector, STREAM:

Methods & Results

You will have noticed that the format of the information weâve produced up to this point isnât very attractive, readable, or easy to interpret. We need to produce publication-quality tables and figures to communicate with our readers. Typically we will summarize our data to condense it into a more easily understood form or display it in graphical form to help tell our story.

In the code-chunk below, Iâm using the graphical abilities provided by the ggplot2 package (Wickham 2016) provided by the tidyverse metapackage (Wickham et al. 2019) to produce a scatter plot of nitrate concentration (NO3) versus sample elevation (SAMPELEV). Note that I include LaTeX code in the axis label by using the TeX() function from the latex2exp package (Meschiari 2022). Note that Quarto will automatically number figures and tables and allow you to cross-reference them in the text.

ggplot(data = df1, aes(x = SAMPELEV, y = NO3)) +
  geom_point(shape = 16, 
             size = 3,
             color = "darkorchid4", # pretty close to WCU purple with 
             alpha = 0.5) +         # alpha (transparency) set to 0.5
  geom_smooth(span = 2) +           # for span, smaller is wigglier
  labs(x = "Elevation where sample was taken (m)",
       y = TeX("$NO_3^- \\; (\\mu mol/L)$")) +
  theme_classic()                   # Produces an "old school" graph

We see that nitrates appear to increase rapidly between 200 and 400 m then to plateau (FigureÂ 1). In the code chunk below, I have created a tibble that summarizes the nitrate data that I can use to produce a publication quality table using the kbl() function from the knitr and kableExtra packages (Zhu 2021, Xie 2023). Note that there are several different packages available for producing tables, and honestly, none have reached the level of maturity that rivals that of the graphing capability. I think the gt package (Iannone et al. 2023) will get there, but it has a steep learning curve.

df1$ELEVCLAS <- ifelse(df1$SAMPELEV <= 400, "Lower", "Higher")

tab1 <- df1 |>
  group_by(ELEVCLAS) |>
  summarize(MeanSAMPELEV = mean(SAMPELEV),
            SDSAMPELEV = sd(SAMPELEV),
            MeanNO3 = mean(NO3),
            SDNO3 = sd(NO3),
            n = n())

kbl(
  tab1,
  digits = c(0,0,0,1,1,2,2,0),
  align = c("lrrrrr"),
  col.names = c(" ", "mean", "sd", "mean", "sd", "n") 
  ) |>
  kable_classic(
    full_width = FALSE,
    bootstrap_options = "striped") |>
  column_spec(
    1:6,
    width = "15mm"
  ) |>
  column_spec(
    4,
    width = "40mm"
  ) |>
  add_header_above(
    c(
      " " = 1, 
      "$$Elevation (m)$$" = 2, 
      "$$NO_3^- \\; (\\mu mol/L)$$" = 2,
      " " = 1
      ),
    align = "right"
  )
TableÂ 1: Nitrate concentrations for samples from Lower elevations (â¤ 400 m) and those from Higher elevations (> 400 m).
$$Elevation (m)$$
$$NO_3^- \; (\mu mol/L)$$
mean sd mean sd n
Higher 560 95 24.6 7.1 33
Lower 314 36 11.3 9.5 5

The mean nitrate concentration for the 33 higher elevation samples was more than double that of the lower elevation samples (TableÂ 1).

I've imported this text file using the read_csv() function provided by the readr package [@readr] included in the tidyverse metapackage [@tidyverse]. This function will create a "[tibble](https://tibble.tidyverse.org/)" which is a special case of ***data.frame***, the standard approach for storing data in memory for most ***R*** operations. In ***R*** jargon, a data.frame is a particular class of ***list***, and lists are flexible ***R*** objects that may contain elements of different types like â numbers, strings, vectors and even other lists. A list can also contain a matrix or a function as its elements. In R, the term ***vectors*** may be more specific or more broad than what you may have been introduced to in a math class. Typically, when you see reference to *vector* in the context of ***R***, it's referring to ***atomic vectors***, that is, they are data structures that contain a single type of data:

-   logical -- TRUE or FALSE,
-   integer - numeric data that are whole integers,
-   double - double precision floating point format (i.e. numbers with decimals),
-   character - non-numeric data,
-   complex -- includes imaginary numbers, or
-   raw - information in byte form.

## Methods & Results

You will have noticed that the format of the information we've produced up to this point isn't very attractive, readable, or easy to interpret. We need to produce publication-quality tables and figures to communicate with our readers. Typically we will summarize our data to condense it into a more easily understood form or display it in graphical form to help tell our story.

In the code-chunk below, I'm using the graphical abilities provided by the ggplot2 package [@ggplot2] provided by the tidyverse metapackage [@tidyverse] to produce a scatter plot of nitrate concentration (**NO3**) versus sample elevation (**SAMPELEV**). Note that I include LaTeX code in the axis label by using the TeX() function from the latex2exp package [@latex2exp]. Note that Quarto will automatically number figures and tables and allow you to cross-reference them in the text.

```{r }
#| label: fig-Fig1
#| fig-cap: "Nitrate concentration versus elevation. Each observation was taken from a different stream."

ggplot(data = df1, aes(x = SAMPELEV, y = NO3)) +
  geom_point(shape = 16, 
             size = 3,
             color = "darkorchid4", # pretty close to WCU purple with 
             alpha = 0.5) +         # alpha (transparency) set to 0.5
  geom_smooth(span = 2) +           # for span, smaller is wigglier
  labs(x = "Elevation where sample was taken (m)",
       y = TeX("$NO_3^- \\; (\\mu mol/L)$")) +
  theme_classic()                   # Produces an "old school" graph
```

We see that nitrates appear to increase rapidly between 200 and 400 m then to plateau (@fig-Fig1). In the code chunk below, I have created a tibble that summarizes the nitrate data that I can use to produce a publication quality table using the kbl() function from the knitr and kableExtra packages [@knitr; @kableExtra]. Note that there are several different packages available for producing tables, and honestly, none have reached the level of maturity that rivals that of the graphing capability. I think the gt package [@gt] will get there, but it has a steep learning curve.

```{r }
#| label: tbl-tab1
#| tbl-cap: "Nitrate concentrations for samples from Lower elevations (â¤ 400 m) and those from Higher elevations (> 400 m)."

df1$ELEVCLAS <- ifelse(df1$SAMPELEV <= 400, "Lower", "Higher")

tab1 <- df1 |>
  group_by(ELEVCLAS) |>
  summarize(MeanSAMPELEV = mean(SAMPELEV),
            SDSAMPELEV = sd(SAMPELEV),
            MeanNO3 = mean(NO3),
            SDNO3 = sd(NO3),

kbl(
  tab1,
  digits = c(0,0,0,1,1,2,2,0),

    full_width = FALSE,
    bootstrap_options = "striped") |>
  column_spec(
    1:6,
    width = "15mm"
  ) |>

    4,

  ) |>

    c(
      " " = 1,
```
